{
  "patterns": [
    {
      "name": "Kinetic vs Potential Energy Mix-Up",
      "what": "Kaiyangnggg sometimes confuses kinetic energy (the energy of movement) with potential energy (stored energy, like in fuels, batteries, or stretched rubber bands).",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[99]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "When asked for a source that is NOT potential energy, he picked fuel (which stores chemical potential energy) instead of wind (which has kinetic energy)."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[24]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He thought the stretched rubber band had kinetic energy, rather than recognizing it stores potential energy until it is released."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When you see questions about energy conversion, ask yourself: 'Is it moving right now?'\n- **Moving objects** (wind, falling water, a flying ball) have **kinetic energy**.\n- **Stored energy** (fuels, food, batteries, stretched springs) is **potential energy**.",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "potential energy",
        "kinetic energy",
        "energy conversion",
        "switched on"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Light and Shadow Rules",
      "what": "Kaiyangnggg occasionally reverses the direction of light rays or forgets that objects closer to a light source cast larger shadows.",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[79]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "When identifying how Peter sees a door, he chose arrows pointing from the door to the lamp, forgetting that light must travel from the source, bounce off the object, and enter the eyes."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[68]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He struggled to match the shapes to their shadow sizes, missing the rule that the shape closest to the torch blocks the most light and casts the largest shadow."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When dealing with light and shadows, remember these two golden rules:\n- **Seeing objects:** Light always travels **from the light source**, bounces **off the object**, and goes **into your eyes**.\n- **Shadow sizes:** The **closer** an object is to the light source, the **larger** its shadow will be.",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "direction of light rays",
        "enable Peter to see",
        "cut out some shapes",
        "shadow"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Heat vs Temperature Mix-Up",
      "what": "Kaiyangnggg sometimes muddles concepts related to heat energy, such as mixing up good and poor conductors, or forgetting that objects gain heat even when their temperature is rising.",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[38]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He thought water in a glass container would cool down the fastest, forgetting that metal is a better conductor and allows heat to escape more quickly."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[35]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "Looking at a heating graph for ice, he thought heat was only gained during melting, missing that the ice and water are also gaining heat when the temperature goes up."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When you see questions about heating or cooling, pause and think about the material and the state:\n- **Conductors:** Metals are **good conductors** (they gain and lose heat fast). Plastics, wood, and air are **poor conductors** (they trap heat).\n- **Heating graphs:** If the heat source is on, the substance is **always gaining heat**, whether the temperature is rising or staying flat during a state change.",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "lowest temperature",
        "gaining heat",
        "poorer conductor",
        "better conductor"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "One Step Short",
      "what": "In open-ended questions, Kaiyangnggg tends to describe what happens but occasionally stops one step short of explaining the scientific reason why it happens.",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[66]",
          "type": "oeq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He correctly noted that cooking two packets of fishballs takes more time, but missed the key scientific reason: there is more mass to heat up."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[64]",
          "type": "oeq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He knew the cup sleeve prevents scalding, but forgot to mention that the corrugated shape traps air, which is a poor conductor of heat."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[46]",
          "type": "oeq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He explained that cacti spines mean they don't give out water often, but missed the exact science phrase: to reduce water loss."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When you see **'explain why'** or **'give a reason'**, make sure to include the specific science keywords.\n- Don't just state the observation (e.g., 'it takes longer').\n- Always add the hidden science cause (e.g., 'because there is **more mass**, so it needs **more heat energy**').",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "explain why",
        "give a reason",
        "explain how"
      ]
    }
  ],
